The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Tuesday, December 23, 2003 				 Four months into job, yet to be paid
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Howrah, Dec. 22: More than 2,500 primary school teachers in Howrah are without pay since their appointment four months ago.																								The office of the district inspector of schools (primary) here said their salary could not be paid because of financial crisis.																								Assistant inspector of schools (primary) Shyamapada Mondal said: We have not been getting the required funds from the treasury to pay the teachers salary owing to a crunch. There is a possibility that the teachers will get their dues in January, he added. 																								The teachers had been appointed in August and September. Astagopal Mondal of Tentulberia Mahakali Prathamik Vidyalaya said 2,600 teachers are living in uncertainty. 																								When the teachers have been recruited through proper channel, it is the duty of the authorities to pay their salary, said Shakti Mondal, leader of the Congress-dominated West Bengal Primary Teachers Association. 																								Howrah district magistrate S. Kishore said he has referred the issue to the school education department.																								About 1,000 schoolteachers in Burdwan, who had joined work in March, went without pay for eight months because of the financial crisis. 
